snippet.textDisplay: Seth I don’t know about everyone els but me and all my mates kinda all agree theses videos are lacking, sorry but I don’t find it entertaining raking a fire road and building a shelf for wood storage, that’s something for berm peak express this channel has curved off the rails a bit there are just too many videos like this being posted in my eyes mainly for easy views, I think we can all agree we want to see you building big fun addictive to ride features (hire or buy an excavator if it’s too hard by hand) but everything is sketchy and made of wood, experiment a little make a decent size jump from dirt one that is smooth and gives u a bit of airtime to chuck whips or other tricks, I have been building a trail for the last 4months with just shovels and dirt no access too wood, and Ye sometimes u make something realise it’s bad and spend some extra time making it good, it’s a public trail and we have had 20+ people so far (just finished it last week) saying it was the best trail in that trail system. Not trying to have a go here your videos are really good I just think the content isn’t great

snippet.textDisplay: Be careful with pulling out stumps abruptly like that. You never know what root system might be holding the stump in and dynamic load, like when the rope pulls taught quickly in this case, is exponentially higher than static load. You could easily shockload your towpoint and rip it, or even worse more than just the hitch, clean off the mounting.
snippet.textOriginal: Be careful with pulling out stumps abruptly like that. You never know what root system might be holding the stump in and dynamic load, like when the rope pulls taught quickly in this case, is exponentially higher than static load. You could easily shockload your towpoint and rip it, or even worse more than just the hitch, clean off the mounting.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Seth, Berm Peak is turning out really cool and i love the videos. One thing i would like to mention, "Any wood that is touching dirt, turns into dirt" when you put any wood on the trail you should either set it in concrete, place it on top of a rock or some other creative idea you come up with. Essentially you don't want any wood touching the dirt because the moisture from the ground will eventually cause the wood to rot and deteriorate even if it is a rot resistant wood such as cedar or pressure treated lumber because it will be a lot more work replacing foundations of jumps or features and the flight deck.
Hope you take the idea into consideration, i wish you and your family well during this time.
